  <section id="git-configure">
    <title>Configure <app>Git</app> first time</title>

    <p>We know that <app>Git</app> records changes to software source. These changes give accountability, that is <em>Who made these changes?</em>. In order for <app>Git</app> to show your name and e-mail address as the author of changes you will be making, you would have to set it. This is a one time configuration, that is, you will be required to set these values if you are using <app>Git</app> for the very first time. Your configuration is stored in the file available at <var>~/.gitconfig</var>.</p>

    <steps>
      <title>Set your name and e-mail in <app>Git</app>:</title>
      <item>
        <p>Type and run <cmd>git config --global user.name "Firstname Lastname"</cmd>, where firstname is your given name and lastname is your surname. For example: <cmd>git config --global user.name "Sindhu Sundar"</cmd>.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <p>Type and run <cmd>git config --global user.email "abc@rst.xy"</cmd>. For example <cmd>git config --global user.email "sindhus@gnome.org"</cmd>.</p>
      </item>
    </steps>

    <note style="tip">
      <p>You also set the editor that will allow you to write commit messages. Type and run <cmd>git config --global core.editor EDITOR</cmd>, where EDITOR is any editor of your choice. For example <cmd>git config --global core.editor gedit</cmd> or <cmd>git config --global core.editor nano</cmd> and so on.</p>
    </note>

  </section>

